    "When habits are insufficient to respond appropriately to moral situations, impulse and intelligence come into play.",
    "Impulse determines the direction of behavioral adjustment, while intelligence consciously reflects on and adjusts behaviors, thereby producing new habits.",
    "Dewey's theory of moral growth can be summarized in Table 11. foot_0",
    "During the pre-training phase, LLMs acquire basic knowledge of the human world by learning from vast amounts of data.",
    "This process closely resembles the first stage of Dewey's moral growth, namely the formation of habits, and is primarily reflected in two aspects."
